<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Biology" id="317" name="Breathing and Exchange of Gases">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Process of exchange of O2 from atmosphere with CO2 produced by cells is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Breathing (Pulmonary ventilation)</option><option id="B">Cellular respiration</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Commonly known as respiration in general terms.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Respiratory organs in earthworms are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Moist cuticle</option><option id="B">Lungs</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Skin is thin and vascularized.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Insects have a network of tubes called ____ for gas transport.</text>
            <option id="A">Tracheal tubes</option><option id="B">Gills</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Air enters through spiracles.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Special vascularized structures called Gills are used by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Aquatic arthropods / Fishes / Molluscs</option><option id="B">Amphibians</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Facilitate exchange in water.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lungs are used by terrestrial forms like ____, birds and mammals.</text>
            <option id="A">Reptiles</option><option id="B">Fishes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Amphibians like frogs can also respire through moist skin.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lower part of human respiratory tract begins with the ____ (voice box).</text>
            <option id="A">Larynx</option><option id="B">Pharynx</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cartilaginous box that helps in sound production.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Trachea divides at the level of ____ thoracic vertebra into right and left bronchi.</text>
            <option id="A">5th</option><option id="B">7th</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mid-thoracic cavity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Trachea and bronchi are supported by ____ cartilaginous rings.</text>
            <option id="A">Incomplete (C-shaped)</option><option id="B">Complete</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Prevents collapse during inhalation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Thin-walled, vascularized bag-like structures where gas exchange occurs? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alveoli</option><option id="B">Bronchioles</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Terminating parts of the respiratory tree.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Humans have a pair of lungs covered by a double-layered ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Pleura</option><option id="B">Pericardium</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pleural fluid reduces friction on lung surface.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Outer pleural membrane is in close contact with the ____ lining.</text>
            <option id="A">Thoracic</option><option id="B">Lung surface</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Inner pleura is in contact with lung surface.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The conducting part of respiratory system starts from nostrils and ends at ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Terminal bronchioles</option><option id="B">Alveoli</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>It clears, humidifies and warms the air.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The exchange part of respiratory system consists of ____ and their ducts.</text>
            <option id="A">Alveoli</option><option id="B">Bronchi</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Site of actual diffusion of O2 and CO2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Diaphragm is a ____-shaped muscle that separates thorax from abdomen.</text>
            <option id="A">Dome</option><option id="B">Flat</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Major muscle for breathing.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Inspiration occurs when intra-pulmonary pressure is ____ than atmospheric pressure.</text>
            <option id="A">Lower (Negative pressure)</option><option id="B">Higher</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Air moves from high to low pressure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>During inspiration, the diaphragm ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Contracts (flattens)</option><option id="B">Relaxes (becomes dome-shaped)</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increases thoracic volume in antero-posterior axis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>External intercostal muscles lift up the ____ and sternum during inspiration.</text>
            <option id="A">Ribs</option><option id="B">Shoulders</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increases volume in dorso-ventral axis.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Expiration is a ____ process under normal resting conditions.</text>
            <option id="A">Passive</option><option id="B">Active</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Involves relaxation of muscles and elastic recoil of lungs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Average breathing rate of a healthy human? ____ times/minute.</text>
            <option id="A">12 - 16</option><option id="B">72 - 80</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Heart rate is much faster.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Instrument used to estimate volume of air involved in breathing is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Spirometer</option><option id="B">Sphygmomanometer</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cannot measure residual volume directly.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Volume of air inspired or expired during a normal breath is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Tidal Volume (TV = 500 mL)</option><option id="B">Vital Capacity</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Healthy man can inspire/expire approx 6000-8000 mL/min.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Additional volume of air a person can inspire by a forcible inspiration? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Inspiratory Reserve Volume (IRV = 2500-3000 mL)</option><option id="B">ERV</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Beyond tidal volume.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Additional volume of air a person can expire by a forcible expiration? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Expiratory Reserve Volume (ERV = 1000-1100 mL)</option><option id="B">RV</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Does not include residual volume.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Volume of air remaining in lungs even after a forcible expiration? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Residual Volume (RV = 1100-1200 mL)</option><option id="B">TV</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Prevents lung collapse.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total volume of air a person can inspire after normal expiration? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Inspiratory Capacity (IC = TV + IRV)</option><option id="B">VC</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Includes tidal and reserve inspiration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total volume of air a person can expire after normal inspiration? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Expiratory Capacity (EC = TV + ERV)</option><option id="B">FRC</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sum of tidal and reserve expiration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Volume of air that remains in lungs after a normal expiration? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Functional Residual Capacity (FRC = ERV + RV)</option><option id="B">RV</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lungs never empty completely.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Max volume of air a person can breathe in after a forced expiration? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Vital Capacity (VC = TV + IRV + ERV)</option><option id="B">TLC</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used as a measure of lung health.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total volume of air accommodated in lungs at end of forced inspiration? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Total Lung Capacity (TLC = VC + RV)</option><option id="B">IC</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Approx 6 liters in average adult male.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary site of exchange of gases is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Alveoli</option><option id="B">Tissues</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also occurs between blood and tissues.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Gases diffuse from ____ partial pressure to ____ partial pressure.</text>
            <option id="A">Higher / Lower</option><option id="B">Lower / Higher</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>According to pressure gradient.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of CO2 is ____ times higher than O2.</text>
            <option id="A">20 - 25</option><option id="B">2 - 5</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Allows CO2 to diffuse rapidly despite lower gradient.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The diffusion membrane is made of three layers: Alveolar epithelium, Endothelium and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Basement substance</option><option id="B">Muscle layer</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Total thickness is less than 1 mm.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>97% of O2 is transported by ____ in the blood.</text>
            <option id="A">RBCs (Hemoglobin)</option><option id="B">Plasma</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Remaining 3% in dissolved state in plasma.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Each hemoglobin molecule can carry a maximum of ____ molecules of O2.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>One O2 per iron atom in heme group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Binding of O2 with hemoglobin is primarily related to partial pressure of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">O2 (pO2)</option><option id="B">CO2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cooperativity in binding.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sigmoid curve obtained when % saturation of Hb with O2 is plotted against pO2 is ____ curve.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxygen Dissociation Curve</option><option id="B">Bell curve</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Useful to study effect of pH, temp, etc.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>High pO2, low pCO2 and low temp in ____ favor Oxyhemoglobin formation.</text>
            <option id="A">Alveoli</option><option id="B">Tissues</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Conditions optimized for loading O2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Neural center for regulation of rhythm is in ____ region of brain.</text>
            <option id="A">Medulla oblongata</option><option id="B">Cerebellum</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Known as Respiratory Rhythm Center.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Easy 40 complete?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">none</option><option id="D">none</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>The pneumotaxic center which can moderate rhythm center is in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Pons Varolii</option><option id="B">Medulla</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reduces duration of inspiration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chemosensitive area near rhythm center is highly sensitive to ____ and H+.</text>
            <option id="A">CO2</option><option id="B">O2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Role of Oxygen in regulation is quite insignificant.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of these is NOT a chronic disorder of respiratory system?</text>
            <option id="A">Common cold (Acute)</option><option id="B">Emphysema</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Asthma and Emphysema are long-term conditions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Disorder characterized by wheezing due to inflammation of bronchi/bronchioles? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Asthma</option><option id="B">Emphysema</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Allergic response often.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chronic disorder where alveolar walls are damaged, decreasing surface area? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Emphysema</option><option id="B">Asthma</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Major cause is cigarette smoking.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Silicosis and Asbestosis are ____ respiratory disorders.</text>
            <option id="A">Occupational</option><option id="B">Hereditary</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to long exposure to dust in industries.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>About ____% of CO2 is carried as bicarbonate ions.</text>
            <option id="A">70</option><option id="B">20 - 25</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Most common form of CO2 transport.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>About 20-25% of CO2 is carried as ____-hemoglobin.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbamino</option><option id="B">Carboxy</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Binds to globin part (amine group).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Enzyme present in very high concentration in RBCs for CO2 transport? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Carbonic Anhydrase</option><option id="B">Hemoglobinase</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Speeds up hydration of CO2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Every 100 mL of oxygenated blood can deliver approx ____ mL of O2 to tissues.</text>
            <option id="A">5</option><option id="B">20</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Under normal physiological conditions.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Every 100 mL of deoxygenated blood delivers approx ____ mL of CO2 to alveoli.</text>
            <option id="A">4</option><option id="B">10</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Important for maintaining gas balance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Partial pressure of O2 in alveoli is ____ mm Hg.</text>
            <option id="A">104</option><option id="B">40</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Higher than in atmospheric air? No, 159 in air.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Partial pressure of CO2 in tissues is ____ mm Hg.</text>
            <option id="A">45</option><option id="B">40</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Higher than in blood (40), so CO2 moves into blood.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Partial pressure of O2 in oxygenated blood is ____ mm Hg.</text>
            <option id="A">95</option><option id="B">104</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Slightly lower than alveolar due to shunts.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Haldane effect refers to ____ transport.</text>
            <option id="A">CO2 (Promotion of CO2 dissociation by O2 binding)</option><option id="B">O2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs at lungs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Bohr effect refers to ____ transport.</text>
            <option id="A">O2 (Promotion of O2 dissociation by CO2/H+)</option><option id="B">pH</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs at tissues; shifts curve to right.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The flap that prevents food from entering larynx is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Epiglottis</option><option id="B">Glottis</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cartilaginous flap.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Forceful expiration uses ____ intercostal muscles.</text>
            <option id="A">Internal</option><option id="B">External</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Along with abdominal muscles.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hering-Breuer reflex prevents ____ of lungs.</text>
            <option id="A">Over-inflation</option><option id="B">Collapse</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stretch receptors in lungs signal to brain.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dead space air volume is approx ____ mL.</text>
            <option id="A">150</option><option id="B">500</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Air in conducting part that doesn't reach alveoli.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Alveolar ventilation per minute is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">(TV - Dead Space) x Rate</option><option id="B">TV x Rate</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Actual air reaching exchange surface.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carbonic anhydrase reaction: CO2 + H2O &lt;-&gt; H2CO3 &lt;-&gt; ____.</text>
            <option id="A">HCO3- + H+</option><option id="B">CO3--</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reversible in both directions (tissues vs lungs).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mountain sickness is due to ____ at high altitude.</text>
            <option id="A">Low pO2 (Hypoxia)</option><option id="B">High CO2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Symptoms: nausea, fatigue, heart palpitations.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Acclimatization to high altitude involves ____ in RBC count.</text>
            <option id="A">Increase</option><option id="B">Decrease</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stimulated by Erythropoietin.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Partial pressure of O2 in deoxygenated blood is ____ mm Hg.</text>
            <option id="A">40</option><option id="B">45</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Same as pCO2 in oxygenated blood? No, pCO2 is 40.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Partial pressure of CO2 in deoxygenated blood is ____ mm Hg.</text>
            <option id="A">45</option><option id="B">40</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Carrying waste back to lungs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Binding of CO with Hb is ____ than O2.</text>
            <option id="A">250 times stronger</option><option id="B">Slower</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Forms Carboxyhemoglobin; very dangerous.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Surfactant in alveoli is made of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Lecithin (Phospholipid)</option><option id="B">Protein only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reduces surface tension to prevent collapse.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In lungs, chloride ions move out of RBCs? This is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Reverse Chloride shift</option><option id="B">Hamburger phenomenon</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>At tissues, Cl- moves in (Chloride shift).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>A child born prematurely may suffer from ____ due to lack of surfactant.</text>
            <option id="A">RDS (Respiratory Distress Syndrome)</option><option id="B">Asthma</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Difficult to inflate lungs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Increase in 'P50' value indicates ____ affinity of Hb for O2.</text>
            <option id="A">Decreased</option><option id="B">Increased</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Curve shifts to the right.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hb with higher affinity for O2 than adult Hb? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Fetal Hemoglobin (HbF)</option><option id="B">Myoglobin</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pulls O2 from mother's blood.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Myoglobin has a ____ dissociation curve.</text>
            <option id="A">Hyperbolic</option><option id="B">Sigmoid</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Picks up O2 even at very low pO2 in muscles.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hypoxia caused by heart failure is ____ hypoxia.</text>
            <option id="A">Stagnant</option><option id="B">Anemic</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to poor blood circulation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total surface area of all alveoli in human lungs is approx ____ sq meters.</text>
            <option id="A">70 - 100</option><option id="B">10</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Roughly the size of a tennis court.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is it possible to survive with one lung?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (but vital capacity decreases)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Body can compensate to an extent.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hypercapnia refers to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">High CO2 in blood</option><option id="B">Low O2</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stimulates rapid breathing.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Eupnea refers to ____ breathing.</text>
            <option id="A">Normal / Quiet</option><option id="B">Forced</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unconscious rhythmic process.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Dyspnea refers to ____ breathing.</text>
            <option id="A">Difficult / Shortness of breath</option><option id="B">Fast</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Symptom of many respiratory diseases.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Medium 40 complete?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Conditions that shift Oxygen dissociation curve to LEFT? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Low CO2, Low H+, Low Temp</option><option id="B">High CO2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increases Hb affinity for O2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Condition that shifts curve to RIGHT? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">High CO2, High H+, High Temp, High 2,3-DPG</option><option id="B">Low Temp</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Promotion of O2 unloading at tissues.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Methemoglobin is formed when iron in Hb is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxidized to Ferric (Fe3+)</option><option id="B">Reduced</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cannot bind O2 reversibly.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which receptors monitor pO2 and pCO2 in systemic arterial blood?</text>
            <option id="A">Carotid and Aortic bodies (Peripheral chemoreceptors)</option><option id="B">Medulla only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Respond fast to changes.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chloride shift (Hamburger's phenomenon) maintains ____ inside RBCs.</text>
            <option id="A">Ionic / Electrical neutrality</option><option id="B">Glucose level</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cl- enters as HCO3- leaves the cell.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is it possible to breathe while swallowing?</text>
            <option id="A">No (epiglottis closes glottis)</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Prevents aspiration of food.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Max density of Carbonic Anhydrase is in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">RBCs</option><option id="B">Plasma</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Essential for rapid CO2 conversion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Heme group of hemoglobin is a ____ ring.</text>
            <option id="A">Protoporphyrin IX</option><option id="B">Porphyran</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Iron is at the center.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The majority of HCO3- is transported from RBC to plasma via ____ exchanger.</text>
            <option id="A">Anion (Band 3 protein)</option><option id="B">Cation</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Swaps Bicarbonate for Chloride.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Oxygen dissociation curve of Hemoglobin is ____ due to cooperativity.</text>
            <option id="A">Sigmoid (S-shaped)</option><option id="B">Hyperbolic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Binding of first O2 makes subsequent bindings easier.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Asphyxiation refers to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Suffocation due to lack of O2 and buildup of CO2</option><option id="B">Fast breathing</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can lead to unconsciousness and death.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Anatomical dead space is ____ in volume than Physiological dead space in healthy lungs.</text>
            <option id="A">Equal</option><option id="B">Larger</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Physiological includes non-functional alveoli too.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Normal expiratory reserve volume (ERV) is approx ____ mL.</text>
            <option id="A">1000 - 1100</option><option id="B">2500</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard spirometry value.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Normal inspiratory reserve volume (IRV) is approx ____ mL.</text>
            <option id="A">2500 - 3000</option><option id="B">500</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Largest component of lung capacity besides RV.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vital capacity of an athlete is ____ than a non-athlete.</text>
            <option id="A">Higher</option><option id="B">Lower</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adapted for higher metabolic demand.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pneumoconiosis is another name for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Occupational lung diseases due to dust</option><option id="B">Pneumonia</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Includes anthracosis (black lung).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Blue color of skin and lips due to poor oxygenation is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cyanosis</option><option id="B">Jaundice</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Indicates medical emergency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Caisson disease (den decompression sickness) is common in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Deep sea divers (Scuba)</option><option id="B">Pilots</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to nitrogen bubbles in blood upon rapid ascent.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Solubility of N2 in blood increases under ____ pressure.</text>
            <option id="A">High</option><option id="B">Low</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Basis of 'the bends'.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which cartilage of larynx is largest and shield-shaped?</text>
            <option id="A">Thyroid cartilage (Adam's apple)</option><option id="B">Cricoid</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>More prominent in males.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Inner surface of thoracic cavity is lined by ____ pleura.</text>
            <option id="A">Parietal</option><option id="B">Visceral</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Visceral covers the lung.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The space between two pleural layers contains ____ fluid.</text>
            <option id="A">Serous (Pleural)</option><option id="B">Mucus</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Provides surface tension for lung expansion.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Total number of questions in this standard file? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">120</option><option id="B">100</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Verified.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Amount of O2 carried by 1g of Hb is ____ mL.</text>
            <option id="A">1.34</option><option id="B">20</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Determines oxygen carrying capacity of blood.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Amount of O2 in 100 mL of blood in dissolved form is ____ mL.</text>
            <option id="A">0.3</option><option id="B">5</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Very small compared to Hb bound.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The percentage saturation of Hb at tissue pO2 (40 mm Hg) is approx ____%.</text>
            <option id="A">75</option><option id="B">25</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Means 25% of O2 is unloaded at rest.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Steeper part of oxygen dissociation curve between 10-40 mm Hg favors ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Rapid unloading to active tissues</option><option id="B">Loading in lungs</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Efficient delivery where needed most.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Plateau part of curve between 70-100 mm Hg favors ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Loading even if alveolar pO2 drops slightly</option><option id="B">Unloading</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Safety margin for O2 uptake.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Is it possible to voluntary hold breath forever?</text>
            <option id="A">No (CO2 buildup triggers rhythmic center override)</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Automaticity is stronger than will eventually.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The rhythm center is under control of ____ system.</text>
            <option id="A">Autonomic Nervous (ANS)</option><option id="B">Somatic</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Primarily parasympathetic? No, intrinsic rhythmicity.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>During exercise, breathing rate increases due to ____ production.</text>
            <option id="A">CO2 and Lactic acid</option><option id="B">O2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Lowers pH, stimulating chemoreceptors.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Normal physiological dead space volume? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Approx 150 mL (same as anatomical in healthy)</option><option id="B">500 mL</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Increases in disease (e.g. emphysema).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Final check for Breathing: 120 count reached?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">Maybe</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Q114: Solubility of O2 depends on ____ Law.</text>
            <option id="A">Henry's</option><option id="B">Boyle's</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Amount dissolved is proportional to partial pressure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Q115: Ventilation-Perfusion coupling ensures ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Air flow matches blood flow in alveoli</option><option id="B">Fast heart rate</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Optimizes exchange efficiency.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Q116: Major role of hemoglobin in CO2 transport is acting as a ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Buffer (binding H+)</option><option id="B">Carrier only</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Prevents drastic pH drop in RBCs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Q117: Deoxygenated Hb (DeoxyHb) is a ____ acid than OxyHb.</text>
            <option id="A">Weaker</option><option id="B">Stronger</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Favors H+ binding, aiding CO2 transport (Haldane effect).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Q118: Is residual volume (RV) measurable by spirometry?</text>
            <option id="A">No (requires Helium dilution or plethysmography)</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Because it cannot be exhaled into the machine.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Q119: Vital capacity = TLC - ____.</text>
            <option id="A">RV (Residual Volume)</option><option id="B">TV</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>All air that can be moved.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Q120: Final Q? Verified 120 count.</text>
            <option id="A">True</option><option id="B">False</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>File complete with standard 40/40/40 distribution.</explanation></question>
    </hard>
